  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Where is the RAW filter in Photoshop CS6?",
  "response": "In Adobe Photoshop CS6, you typically use Adobe Camera Raw (ACR) to work with RAW files. Here's how to access and use the Camera Raw filter:\n\n1. **Opening a RAW file**:\n   - When you open a RAW file directly in Photoshop CS6, it automatically launches the Camera Raw interface where you can make detailed adjustments to your image.\n\n2. **Using Camera Raw as a filter**:\n   - If you want to apply Camera Raw adjustments to an existing layer or image, you need to use the Camera Raw filter. This is found in the Filter menu.\n\nTo apply the Camera Raw filter:\n\n1. **Open your image in Photoshop CS6**.\n2. **Convert your layer to a Smart Object** (optional but recommended for non-destructive editing):\n    - Right-click on the layer and select \"Convert to Smart Object\".\n3. **Access the Camera Raw filter**:\n    - Go to `Filter` -> `Camera Raw Filter`.\n\nThis will open the Camera Raw interface where you can make your adjustments and then apply them to your image. The adjustments include exposure, white balance, tone curves, color correction, and more.\n\nRemember, converting your layer to a Smart Object lets you apply the Camera Raw filter as a non-destructive edit, preserving your original image data and allowing you to modify or remove the filter later if needed.",
